Introduction¶

This analysis is based on a set of data extracted from early 2000 in the banking system, it captures a wholistic loan disburement naratives with indept details of performing and non performing loans and other indices of granting loan like Employment status, occupation, term and so on. This data will also lead to answering questions below and more:

What factors affect a loan’s outcome status?

What affects the borrower’s APR or interest rate?

Are there differences between loans depending on how large the original loan amount was?

What is the distribution of interest rates borrowers?¶

In [11]:
def dist_plot(arg,size,xliml,xlimu):
    '''Plotting on a standard scaled plot'''   
    bins = np.arange(0, df_loan[arg].max()+size, size)
    plt.figure(figsize=[10, 8])
    plt.hist(data = df_loan, x = arg, bins = bins)
    plt.xlabel(arg)
    plt.xlim(xliml,xlimu)
    plt.show()
    
dist_plot('BorrowerRate',0.07,0,0.5)

From the hist chart above Borrowers rate have highest counts between 0.10 and 0.2 on loan amounts

Distribution of borrower debt income ratio¶

In [16]:
# distribution of debt income ratio
plt.figure(figsize = [10,5])
sns.distplot(df_loan.DebtToIncomeRatio, bins = 120,kde = False)
plt.xlim(-.1, 1)
plt.xlabel('DebtToIncomeRatio')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Distribution of Borrower Debt to Income Ratio');

The graph is slightly skewed to the right with a downward slope and the highest count of debt income ratio at 0.2, this implies that borrowers with high DSR ratio have lower access to loan because they considered high risk for investors

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of Borrower debt to income is slightly skewed to the right with a downward slope and the highest count of debt income ratio at 0.2 and lowest count at 0.9. the data looked unimodal and does not need require transformation

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The distributions of stated monthly income is highly right skewed. Most stated monthly incomes are less than 30k, but some of them are incredibly high, like greater than 100k. Surprisingly, most of borrowers with greater than 100k monthly income only loan less than 5k dollars. So, the very large stated monthly income may be made up. Overall, Less than 0.3 percent borrowers have stated monthly income greater than 30k, these can be seemed as outlier for the following analysis, so it is better to remove borrower records with income greater than 30k.

Does monthly income determine monthly payment?¶

In [18]:

The plot above shows an inverse correlation between monthly income and monthly payments, a lower income require higher monthly payment and vice versa .

ax.set_yticklabels([],minor = True);

This graph has a rythmic relationship with no record attributed to the Retired, Part-time and Not available employment status for the 12 months term category

In [22]:
# Employment effect on relationship of APR and loan amount
g=sns.FacetGrid(data=df_loan, aspect=1.2, height=5, col='EmploymentStatus', col_wrap=4)
g.map(sns.regplot, 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'BorrowerAPR', x_jitter=0.04, scatter_kws={'alpha':0.2});
g.add_legend();

The plot above shows a higher number of employed and full-time against loan original amount which signifies direct posisitive relations, the graph also shows that higher BorrowerAPR is attributed to Other and Not employed employment status which makes it high risk

Conclusions¶

This analysis is based on prosper data set of a total of 113937 and 16 columns for analysis, its is deduced that customer loan amount range from minimum of 10k to max at 483k witth term ranging from 12 to 60 months. The Borrower rate has a negative correlation with Loan amount disbursed whith a downward straightline slope.
